NASA will ensure jobs for youths and economic growth in Tharaka Nithi if it is elected, presidential candidate Raila Odinga said on Friday.He dismissed as propaganda Jubilee&rsquo;s claims that NASA will not expand the economy or create jobs.Raila was welcomed by county residents who said they will support the party if it promises to deliver development.&ldquo;... hapa tumekuja kama wakulima wa kahawa, wa majani chai na najua wako na shida ... sisi tutahakikisha vijana watapata ajira...&rdquo; he said.(&ldquo;We have come here as coffee and tea farmers and we know they have problems [but] we will ensure the youth get employment.&rdquo;)&ldquo;Canaan is our destiny and Tharaka Nithi is part of the Kenyans heading to Canaan. &ldquo;Mara hii hakuna kuiba kura tena (This time round there will be no stealing of votes),&rdquo; Raila said.He was with his running mate Kalonzo Musyoka and principal Moses Wetang&rsquo;ula.Earlier, his supporters expressed optimism that the opposition would uplift the region.&ldquo;We want them to just talk about the development of this region and not politick,&rdquo; one resident said.Another said they were ready to listen to the NASA principals and want them to sell their agenda to the county.&ldquo;We are happy they are here. We will listen to them,&rdquo; he said.Raila, 72, will face President Uhuru Kenyatta of Jubilee. The opposition leader unsuccessfully ran for President in 1997, 2007 and in 2013.He was Prime Minister from 2008-2012 under a power-sharing deal in the Grand Coalition Government with President Mwai Kibaki.The deal was struck to end violence that rocked the country, following the disputed December 27, 2007, presidential election.More than 1,300 people were killed and some 650,000 Kenyans were displaced.